elaxes the lower oesophageal sphincter"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe main effect of \u003Cstrong\u003Epromoting acid production\u003C/strong\u003E occurs through two mechanisms: direct stimulation of parietal cells and indirect stimulation via enterochromaffin-like (ECL) cells which release histamine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuppresses stomach contractions\u003C/strong\u003E - Gastrin enhances gastric motility\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreases mucosal cell growth\u003C/strong\u003E - Gastrin stimulates growth of the gastric mucosa\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks histamine secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - Gastrin stimulates histamine release from ECL cells\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERelaxes the lower oesophageal sphincter\u003C/strong\u003E - Gastrin increases sphincter tone\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EG cells in the gastric antrum release gastrin when stimulated by proteins in food, stomach stretching, and vagal nerve signals. Rising acid levels provide negative feedback to reduce gastrin secretion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["G cells in the gastric antrum release gastrin in response to food and stomach stretching","Gastrin\u0027s main role is promoting acid secretion through both direct and indirect pathways"],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Asbury, C., Rieke, F., Hille, B., Bothwell, M., \u0026 Tuthill, J. (2023) Physiology. Simple Book Publishing. https://uw.pressbooks.pub/physiology/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"i